{"status":"success","result":"Now I have everything I need. Full audit complete.\n\n---\n\n*Jarvis v0.1.0 — CTO Backlog*\n\n---\n\n*P1 — Correctness & Reliability*\n\n• *No tests for `classifyMessage`* — it's the most critical path in the system and has zero test coverage. `callOllama`, `handleToolCall`, `resolveModel` are all tested; the new classifier is not. First thing to fix.\n\n• *`keep_alive: 60` on Secretary in `classifyMessage`* — Secretary is called on every single turn. It will never evict in practice. Either pin it to `-1` like the Coordinator, or at least document that it's effectively always warm. Right now the code lies about its own memory behaviour.\n\n• *`classifyMessage` truncates prompt to 600 chars* — line 387: `text.slice(0, 600)`. Long messages (code pastes, essays, multi-part questions) get misclassified because the Secretary only sees the opening. Should send more, or send a smarter excerpt.\n\n• *Artist/Cinematographer JSON parse fails silently* — confirmed at lines 968-974 and 1038-1044. When qwen2.5vl:72b doesn't return valid JSON, raw model output becomes the generation prompt with no warning. User gets a weird image with no explanation. Should surface as an error or at minimum log it visibly.\n\n• *Resource contention on qwen2.5vl:72b* — triple duty: Artist, Cinematographer, AND multi-image descriptor. A 6-minute video generation will queue or timeout incoming image description calls. No handling for this race condition anywhere.\n\n---\n\n*P2 — Performance & UX*\n\n• *Fast-path for trivial messages* — \"ok\", \"thanks\", \"lol\" all pay a ~1s Secretary call before getting a response. Pre-check before classify: < 6 words AND no action verbs AND no `?` AND no backticks → skip straight to chat/low. Saves latency on the most common conversational turns.\n\n• *Secretary draft has no conversation history* — `classifyMessage` sends only the current message to Secretary (line 387). When Secretary drafts an answer to a follow-up question (\"what about the second option?\"), it has no context and will draft confidently wrong answers. History slice (last 4 messages) should be included.\n\n• *`AUTO_ESCALATE_PATTERN` inconsistency* — upfront routing is now semantic; mid-response failure detection is still regex on apology phrases. Models that fail confidently and don't apologise never escalate. Should be replaced with a post-response Secretary check: \"did this fully address the question?\"\n\n• *Feedback loop still a concept, not a feature* — binary user signal on routing correctness has no capture, storage, or reinjection mechanism. Concrete implementation: log `[classify]` decisions → on user correction signal, append to a `routing-corrections.jsonl` → periodically distill into few-shot examples in the classify prompt.\n\n---\n\n*P3 — Robustness & Code Quality*\n\n• *Tool call rounds cap at 5 with no notification* — line 1281 silently exits the loop. If a legitimate task hits the limit (reading multiple files, multi-step commands), Jarvis just stops and returns whatever partial response it has. Should at minimum tell the user the loop was interrupted.\n\n• *Follow-up fetch has no error handling* — line 1329: the `followUp` call after tool results doesn't check `.ok` or wrap in try/catch. The initial `callOllama` call correctly throws on non-ok (line 1267). Inconsistency that will surface as an obscure unhandled rejection.\n\n• *`thinkingMs` at line 1369 is dead code* — computed, never used. Delete.\n\n• *`ipcDir2` at line 1057* — duplicate variable for `/workspace/ipc/messages` that already exists as `ipcDir`. Minor but adds noise.\n\n• *`TASK_DETECT` regex at line 1734* — another large pattern-matching regex, this time for the status summary label. Lower stakes than routing but same fragility class. Worth noting as future technical debt.\n\n• *Tests missing for `getEscalationTier`* — the escalation ladder logic is simple but critical. Easy to test, currently not tested.\n\n---\n\n*P4 — Process & Architecture*\n\n• *Architecture decision log missing* — no record of why `deepseek-r1:32b` was dropped, why qwen2.5vl does triple duty, why the escalation ladder is structured as it is. As the system grows, these decisions will get re-litigated unnecessarily.\n\n• *Changelog gaps v0.0.15–0.0.29* — identical \"Fresh off the press\" entries mean the historical record for that sprint is lost. Not recoverable but worth noting as a process failure to avoid repeating.\n\n• *Prompt not externalised* — the classify prompt is hardcoded. Every tuning iteration requires a full deploy. Moving it to a file in the group folder would allow prompt updates without rebuilding the container.\n\n---\n\n*Quick summary by effort vs. impact:*\n• Highest ROI right now: Secretary `keep_alive`, prompt truncation fix, fast-path for trivial messages, tests for `classifyMessage`\n• Biggest risk unaddressed: resource contention on qwen2.5vl:72b, silent Artist JSON fallback\n• Most important long-term: feedback loop implementation, architecture decision log","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
